Globalization's diseases
Globalization is being tested more severely than ever before.
Tensions are brewing everywhere.
The vast majority of Sub-Saharan Africa, South America, the Middle East, and Central Asia are either stagnating or struggling in economic decline.
North America, Western Europe, and Japan are mired in slow growth and risk another recession.
War now threatens in Iraq.
For proponents of open markets and free trade, this situation poses major challenges.
Why is globalization so threatened?
Why do its benefits seem concentrated in only a few places?
Can a more balanced globalization be implemented?
There is no simple answer to these questions.
Open markets are necessary for economic growth, but they are far from sufficient.
Certain regions of the world have derived significant benefits from globalization, particularly East Asia and China in recent years.
Other regions, however, have gained only meager benefits, especially Sub-Saharan Africa.
The US government claims that poor countries are responsible for most of the problems they face.
The slow growth in Africa, American leaders assert, is caused by the ineptitude of the African government.
However, life is more complicated than the Bush administration believes.
Consider the best-governed countries in Africa: Ghana, Tanzania, Malawi, Gambia.
Each has experienced lower living standards over the past two decades while many Asian countries that ranked among the last in international comparisons of governance (Pakistan, Bangladesh, Myanmar, and Sri Lanka) have experienced better economic growth.
It is true that economic performance is determined not only by governance standards but also by geopolitics, geography, and economic structure.
Countries with large populations and therefore large domestic markets tend to grow more quickly than countries with small populations.
(As with all economic trends of this kind, there are counterexamples.)
Coastal countries tend to perform better than landlocked countries.
Countries with high levels of malaria tend to experience slower growth than those with lower levels of malaria.
Developing countries that border rich markets, like Mexico, tend to perform better than those that are far from major markets.
These differences are of great importance.
If rich countries do not care about these structural problems, the gaps between winners and losers will continue to widen.
If rich countries shift responsibility onto unlucky countries by claiming they are culturally or politically somehow unfit to benefit from globalization, we will not only create deeper pockets of poverty but also intensify conflicts.
This, in turn, will lead to increased levels of violence, hostile reactions, and terrorism.
It is therefore time to move towards a more serious approach to globalization than what rich countries, and particularly America, offer.
This approach must start with the most urgent task, namely addressing the fundamental needs of the world's poorest peoples.
In some cases, their suffering can be alleviated primarily through better governance within their own countries.
But in others, a honest look at the gathered evidence will reveal that the main causes of poverty relate to diseases, climate instability, poor soil, distances to markets, etc.
An honest assessment would further indicate that the poorest countries lack the ability to raise sufficient funds to solve such problems on their own.
Instead of seeing rich countries give more lectures on the bad governance of poor countries, real solutions require that rich countries provide enough financial assistance to overcome the most deeply rooted barriers.
A case will starkly illustrate this situation.
Controlling diseases requires a healthcare system capable of providing life-saving medicines and basic preventive services such as bed nets to combat malaria and vitamins to fight nutritional deficiencies.
This system costs at least about 40 dollars per person and year.
This sum is just a fraction for rich countries that spend systematically over 2,000 dollars per person and year on health, but it exceeds the means of poor countries like Malawi, which have annual incomes of 200 dollars per person.
A functioning healthcare system would cost more than the entire government revenue!
Even though Malawi is well-governed, its population will continue to die in large numbers from diseases until it receives adequate assistance.
The success of globalization requires us to think more like doctors and less like preachers.
Instead of scolding the poor for their "sins," we must offer careful diagnoses, as any good doctor would, for each country and region, to understand the fundamental factors that hinder their growth and economic development.
In regions like the Andes and Central Asia, the problem primarily stems from geographic isolation.
There, the task is to build roads, air links, and internet connectivity to help these remote regions establish productive links with the world.
Rich countries must contribute to financing these projects.
In Sub-Saharan Africa, the main challenges lie in controlling diseases, soil fertility, and developing educational opportunities.
Again, greater foreign assistance is required.
In other regions, the primary problems include lack of water, discrimination against women or other groups, or a variety of specific issues.
It is now time to take the inherent complexities of globalization seriously.
The ideology of one size fits all for the Washington Consensus is outdated.
Before war breaks out, it is urgent to tackle the hard task of ensuring that everyone benefits from globalization.
We can achieve this if we remove ideological blinkers from the rich and mobilize a partnership between the rich and the poor.
Our common future depends on it.
